<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How much grass seed do I need for a new lawn?", answer: "Cool-season new-lawn rates are roughly 2 lb per 1,000 sq ft for Kentucky bluegrass, 4 lb for fine fescue, and 8 lb for tall fescue and perennial ryegrass. Warm-season new-lawn rates are 1.5 lb for bermudagrass, 2 lb for zoysia, 0.5 lb for centipede, and 7 lb for bahiagrass. A 5,000 sq ft tall fescue lawn needs 40 lb of seed; a 5,000 sq ft bermudagrass lawn needs 7.5 lb." },
  { question: "How much seed for overseeding?", answer: "Overseeding uses roughly half the new-lawn rate because you are adding seed to an existing stand of grass. For tall fescue, that is 4 lb per 1,000 sq ft; for Kentucky bluegrass, 1 lb; for perennial ryegrass, 4 lb. Overseed in early fall for cool-season grasses and in late spring for warm-season grasses. Aerate first so seed can reach soil." },
  { question: "When should I plant grass seed?", answer: "Cool-season grasses germinate best in early fall (August 15 to September 15 in most of the US) when soil is warm and air is cool. Spring planting works but has more weed competition. Warm-season grasses go in late spring to early summer after soil reaches 65°F consistently. Never seed in summer heat or during a freeze." },
  { question: "Kentucky bluegrass vs tall fescue — how much seed?", answer: "Kentucky bluegrass has very small seeds (about 2 million seeds per pound), so a 2 lb per 1,000 sq ft rate still delivers 4 million seeds per 1,000 sq ft. Tall fescue has much larger seeds (about 227,000 per pound), so even at 8 lb per 1,000 sq ft the seed count is lower — just under 2 million. Both rates produce a thick lawn; they just reflect seed size." },
  { question: "Can I use too much grass seed?", answer: "Yes. Over-seeding makes seedlings compete for light, water, and nutrients, producing weak grass that fails to thicken. Stick to the recommended rate for your species. If seed has been sitting for more than 2 years, germination drops 10 to 20 percent per year, so increase the rate 25 percent for old seed — but never double-up for a perceived fast fill." }
]) %>

